WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.600
Hi, my name is Mel Gregory, and I am a software engineer at RStudio, and I work on the team

00:00:14.600 --> 00:00:18.920
that's building RStudio Cloud, which we've heard about a little bit today.

00:00:18.920 --> 00:00:20.120
And that's what I'm here to talk to you about.

00:00:20.120 --> 00:00:24.879
So this talk is primarily geared toward people who are teaching data science or statistics

00:00:24.879 --> 00:00:28.379
or anything else where your students might want to do some data analysis.

00:00:28.379 --> 00:00:31.160
And to that end, I'm going to briefly detail a little bit about how RStudio Cloud works

00:00:31.160 --> 00:00:34.340
for anyone who hasn't yet seen it, and I will spend the rest of my time today demonstrating

00:00:34.340 --> 00:00:39.419
why and how to use RStudio Cloud in a teaching context, how it can make teaching a course

00:00:39.419 --> 00:00:43.380
or a workshop easier, and along the way, I will highlight a few best practices for doing

00:00:43.380 --> 00:00:44.380
this.

00:00:44.380 --> 00:00:47.340
I will also talk about some current limitations and touch on a few additional learning resources

00:00:47.340 --> 00:00:49.820
that RStudio Cloud makes available, namely primers.

00:00:49.820 --> 00:00:54.700
Okay, so let's imagine that I'm teaching an intro to data science class for our purposes

00:00:54.700 --> 00:00:55.700
here.

00:00:55.700 --> 00:00:58.380
So my students will be doing data analysis using R, but probably don't have a ton of

00:00:58.380 --> 00:01:00.500
prior experience writing code.

00:01:00.500 --> 00:01:04.540
So to get started, they might do something like this, maybe ahead of time, but probably

00:01:04.540 --> 00:01:06.500
on the first day.

00:01:06.500 --> 00:01:11.459
Install R. Install RStudio.

00:01:11.459 --> 00:01:13.660
Maybe install some packages, cool.

00:01:13.660 --> 00:01:17.500
And then they're going to troubleshoot some installation problems, and I might just have

00:01:17.500 --> 00:01:19.099
to help here.

00:01:19.099 --> 00:01:24.660
And then finally, they get here, and you know, that's a lot to do before writing any code,

00:01:24.660 --> 00:01:27.059
and it can be tricky, especially if you're new to this.

00:01:27.059 --> 00:01:30.540
And given the myriad different systems that my students might bring with them, it's actually

00:01:30.540 --> 00:01:34.059
a lot for me to potentially troubleshoot, too, if things go sideways.

00:01:34.059 --> 00:01:37.419
So on the other hand, the first day could be this.

00:01:37.419 --> 00:01:43.220
Go to rstudio.cloud in your web browser, log in or sign up, create a new project, and you're

00:01:43.220 --> 00:01:44.580
there.

00:01:44.580 --> 00:01:47.779
So there's no installation here, and there's no setup for students to do, aside from signing

00:01:47.779 --> 00:01:51.019
up for an account, and when using RStudio Cloud, students will all be running the same

00:01:51.019 --> 00:01:54.900
versions of R and the RStudio ID automatically, so there's no installation troubleshooting

00:01:54.900 --> 00:01:56.540
to do there, either.

00:01:56.540 --> 00:01:59.860
