00:02:15.020 --> 00:02:17.860
Getting up and running quickly provides an invaluable sense of progress here, and we

00:02:17.860 --> 00:02:21.100
can come back to these details when they have a bit more context.

00:02:21.100 --> 00:02:23.100
So RStudio Cloud.

00:02:23.100 --> 00:02:27.139
Briefly, RStudio Cloud is the RStudio IDE, available as a service that you can access

00:02:27.139 --> 00:02:29.779
from anywhere you have an internet connection and a modern web browser.

00:02:29.779 --> 00:02:33.419
It doesn't require any IT support or local installation, and you can sign up for an account

00:02:33.419 --> 00:02:35.059
and you can use it today.

00:02:35.059 --> 00:02:38.979
We created RStudio Cloud to make it easy to do, share, teach, and learn data science using

00:02:38.979 --> 00:02:42.419
R, and in support of that mission, we've built a ton of extra features to make it easier

00:02:42.419 --> 00:02:45.740
to organize work, teach classes, learn R, and share analyses.

00:02:45.740 --> 00:02:49.380
So first, a little bit of basic terminology.

00:02:49.380 --> 00:02:52.940
In RStudio Cloud, the fundamental unit of work is a project.

00:02:52.940 --> 00:02:58.100
It encapsulates your R code packages and data files and provides isolation from other analyses.

00:02:58.100 --> 00:03:02.699
So this is analogous to projects in a local installation of the RStudio IDE.

00:03:02.699 --> 00:03:06.820
A space is a place for a group of people to organize and collaborate on work.

00:03:06.820 --> 00:03:10.580
In addition to a personal workspace that everyone gets automatically, you can also create spaces

00:03:10.580 --> 00:03:15.500
with roles and permissions to control project sharing and visibility for space members.

00:03:15.500 --> 00:03:20.979
So not coincidentally, these spaces work well for courses, sections, and workshops.

00:03:20.979 --> 00:03:23.300
Spaces have four different possible roles.

00:03:23.300 --> 00:03:26.139
The creator of a space is automatically assigned the admin role.

00:03:26.139 --> 00:03:28.500
This role is recommended for instructors.

00:03:28.500 --> 00:03:32.300
Admins have total control over the space and can see and edit all projects in it.

00:03:32.300 --> 00:03:34.080
Next we have moderators.

00:03:34.080 --> 00:03:36.800
This role works well for TAs if you have them.

00:03:36.800 --> 00:03:40.339
Like an admin, a moderator can see and edit all projects in a space regardless of visibility.

00:03:40.339 --> 00:03:42.199
So more on that in just a minute.

00:03:42.199 --> 00:03:44.500
The contributor role is a good choice for students.

00:03:44.500 --> 00:03:46.539
Contributors can create new projects in the space.

00:03:46.539 --> 00:03:49.179
And viewers can see the space, but they can't create new projects in it.

00:03:49.179 --> 00:03:53.660
So this role could work well for someone who is auditing the class, for example.

00:03:53.660 --> 00:03:57.460
Whether or not a project can be seen by someone else is controlled by its visibility.

00:03:57.460 --> 00:04:00.479
A project can be public, that is, shared with everyone, or private.

00:04:00.479 --> 00:04:03.580
Private projects in a space can be viewed by the author and also the admins and moderators

00:04:03.580 --> 00:04:05.179
of the space.

00:04:05.179 --> 00:04:08.419
Private projects are indicated with a lock icon like that.

00:04:08.419 --> 00:04:09.419
