So, in the same section, we have a link to the guide to tell you about how to use RStudio

00:15:37.900 --> 00:15:45.400
Cloud if I'm going too fast here, a collection of data camp courses using R, our downloadable

00:15:45.400 --> 00:15:49.840
cheat sheets all right in here, and a section on what's new in RStudio Cloud.

00:15:49.840 --> 00:15:50.840
This is a good one to pay attention to.

00:15:50.840 --> 00:15:52.960
We'll highlight big new changes in here.

00:15:52.960 --> 00:15:56.799
Okay, so back to slides.

00:15:56.799 --> 00:16:03.000
Okay, so the workflow that I just described makes good use of copy projects via assignments.

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:06.000
However, you might want your students to create new projects themselves.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:10.599
If they're pulling code from an existing Git repository, for example, the new project menu

00:16:10.599 --> 00:16:12.200
has an option for that.

00:16:12.200 --> 00:16:13.580
Git is really great.

00:16:13.580 --> 00:16:18.039
This option will bring up a dialog to enter a repository URL, and RStudio Cloud will create

00:16:18.039 --> 00:16:19.739
a new project for it.

00:16:19.739 --> 00:16:22.619
Once the project is created, you may have to log in, but once you do, you'll have all

00:16:22.619 --> 00:16:25.099
of your source from Git right there.

00:16:25.099 --> 00:16:28.739
One final helpful thing, you can set up your space such that all new projects created in

00:16:28.739 --> 00:16:32.059
it will include a default set of packages and files.

00:16:32.059 --> 00:16:35.500
This is done by selecting a base project in the space settings.

00:16:35.500 --> 00:16:38.880
You can actually take advantage of this feature when creating assignments for your class.

00:16:38.880 --> 00:16:42.179
If your assignments all need the same set of packages, say you want the tidyverse in

00:16:42.179 --> 00:16:45.700
all of them, you can create a project in your space with those packages installed and

00:16:45.700 --> 00:16:47.659
set it as the base project.

00:16:47.659 --> 00:16:50.979
All new projects will have those packages installed automatically.

00:16:50.979 --> 00:16:55.659
Note that base projects are not retroactive and won't apply to previously created projects.

00:16:55.659 --> 00:16:57.179
You can learn more about this in the guide.

00:16:57.179 --> 00:17:01.700
I'm sorry to tease a tantalizing bit of setup like this, but I'm really short on time.

00:17:01.700 --> 00:17:05.020
RStudio Cloud currently has a few limits to be aware of.

00:17:05.020 --> 00:17:06.859
RStudio Cloud is still an alpha product.

00:17:06.859 --> 00:17:11.459
We do not currently support simultaneous collaborative at A. If your students need to collaborate

00:17:11.459 --> 00:17:15.420
on work in this way, we suggest using a Git-based repository for code.

00:17:15.420 --> 00:17:18.699
Using source control is not a terrible idea regardless.

00:17:18.699 --> 00:17:22.500
Currently projects are limited to one gig of RAM, and by default you can create one

00:17:22.500 --> 00:17:25.920
additional private space with up to 10 members and 25 projects.

00:17:25.920 --> 00:17:29.780
If you need extra spaces or extra capacity, please reach out to us, particularly if you

00:17:29.780 --> 00:17:33.500
want to use RStudio Cloud for teaching, and we will do our best to accommodate you.

00:17:33.500 --> 00:17:38.260
You can see a capacity message on the projects and members listing page if you hit that point,

00:17:38.260 --> 00:17:41.060
and you can request more capacity via the button there.

00:17:41.660 --> 00:17:43.699
Some best practices in summary.

00:17:43.699 --> 00:17:46.339
First, use RStudio Cloud for teaching.

00:17:46.339 --> 00:17:49.180
I am biased, but I think it's really great.

00:17:49.180 --> 00:17:54.540
Second, use spaces to get the helpful features that we've just talked about, like assignments,

00:17:54.540 --> 00:17:55.819
which takes me to third.

00:17:55.819 --> 00:17:57.760
Make use of assignments and spaces.

00:17:57.760 --> 00:18:00.699
This will make sure that your students do not inadvertently lose work because they forgot

00:18:00.699 --> 00:18:02.459
to create a permanent copy.

00:18:02.459 --> 00:18:06.020
Also because only public projects can be assignments, this ensures that your students will have

00:18:06.020 --> 00:18:09.060
access to the project you intended to share with them.

00:18:09.459 --> 00:18:13.260
Third, take advantage of space rules and permissions to make sure students can only see what they

00:18:13.260 --> 00:18:14.260
should.

00:18:14.260 --> 00:18:15.760
And finally, test things out ahead of time.

00:18:15.760 --> 00:18:19.459
Make sure you're not going to hit RAM limits and that you have the capacity that you need.

00:18:19.459 --> 00:18:23.939
So I want to briefly mention that while I've talked a lot about teaching in this talk,

00:18:23.939 --> 00:18:27.099
RStudio Cloud can be used for other situations too.

00:18:27.099 --> 00:18:29.819
If you want to use it to share your analyses, for example, please do come and take it for

00:18:29.819 --> 00:18:31.380
a spin.

00:18:31.380 --> 00:18:34.660
You can create projects in your personal workspace and share them with others.

00:18:34.660 --> 00:18:38.619
And while the memory limits apply to all projects, the project capacity limit is much higher

00:18:38.619 --> 00:18:41.219
in your workspace by default.

00:18:41.219 --> 00:18:44.500
And unlike in spaces, shared projects created in your workspace can be seen by anyone with

00:18:44.500 --> 00:18:48.380
a project URL in RStudio Cloud account, so they're a little easier to share out.

00:18:48.380 --> 00:18:49.900
You can learn more about that in the guide.

00:18:49.900 --> 00:18:52.579
So we are actively releasing new features all the time.

00:18:52.579 --> 00:18:56.739
Please keep an eye out on the What's New section, and we'll highlight big changes there.

00:18:56.739 --> 00:19:00.099
Also know in addition to the big stuff, we roll out small improvements often.

00:19:00.099 --> 00:19:02.439
If you have questions or feedback, we'll use RStudio Cloud.

00:19:02.439 --> 00:19:06.180
Please reach out to us on community via the dedicated RStudio Cloud category.

00:19:06.180 --> 00:19:08.599
We're pretty active there, and we'd love to know what you think.

00:19:08.599 --> 00:19:11.680
